    {
      "id": "SkUogcENggjOgponZaUa8",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 416.22067820549205,
      "y": 186.6509429402326,
      "width": 1097.879150390625,
      "height": 175,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3b",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 410782304,
      "version": 307,
      "versionNonce": 393605728,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771563381971,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "background: \nweb mapping service - services such as statelite imagery, street maps, real time traffic conditions, route planning\nhelp users find direction\n\n1 billion DAU,\n99% coverage of the world,\n25 million updates daily of real time loc info",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "background: \nweb mapping service - services such as statelite imagery, street maps, real time traffic conditions, route planning\nhelp users find direction\n\n1 billion DAU,\n99% coverage of the world,\n25 million updates daily of real time loc info",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "6jnnyRbYUCKv-GNP2b3Qb",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 414.51465755213417,
      "y": 388.24338313515693,
      "width": 1284.779052734375,
      "height": 650,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3d",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 507735968,
      "version": 1207,
      "versionNonce": 1509355104,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [
        {
          "id": "aFH617kzNCUh4rFmgNIu7",
          "type": "arrow"
        }
      ],
      "updated": 1771568228636,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "clarify:\nwhat are we solving here?\nhow do we want to measure success?\nwhat should we prioritize? what system exactly\nclarify the scale(MEM & QPS)\nclarify user experience(latency & CAP)\n\nfunc reqs:\n- user sends loc update to our system [loc update]\n- user can put start & end, and get (shortest) route to dest [NAV]\n    - user also gets ETA for route [ETA]\n- user can see places around him/her [Map rendering]\n\nnon func reqs:\n- latency (<10ms) to retrieve shortest route to dest\n- *latency (<10ms) of map rendering on client side\n- handle high QPS of location udpates from millions of user (TBD)\n- availability >> consistency (where the route does not necessarily always be the best as long as there is a good enough path way)\n- MEM scaling (alot of map data & user data) (TBD)\n\nfrom the book:\n-> accuracy: user shld not be given wrong direction\n-> smoot hnav: on client side, user shld experience smooth map rendering\n-> data & battery usage: client should use as little data & batt as possible; impt for mobile devices\n-> general availability & scalability reqs\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "clarify:\nwhat are we solving here?\nhow do we want to measure success?\nwhat should we prioritize? what system exactly\nclarify the scale(MEM & QPS)\nclarify user experience(latency & CAP)\n\nfunc reqs:\n- user sends loc update to our system [loc update]\n- user can put start & end, and get (shortest) route to dest [NAV]\n    - user also gets ETA for route [ETA]\n- user can see places around him/her [Map rendering]\n\nnon func reqs:\n- latency (<10ms) to retrieve shortest route to dest\n- *latency (<10ms) of map rendering on client side\n- handle high QPS of location udpates from millions of user (TBD)\n- availability >> consistency (where the route does not necessarily always be the best as long as there is a good enough path way)\n- MEM scaling (alot of map data & user data) (TBD)\n\nfrom the book:\n-> accuracy: user shld not be given wrong direction\n-> smoot hnav: on client side, user shld experience smooth map rendering\n-> data & battery usage: client should use as little data & batt as possible; impt for mobile devices\n-> general availability & scalability reqs\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "C1wLtCummJAPhQmd04dhr",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -373.55615296981057,
      "y": 496.41475931632425,
      "width": 692.4795532226562,
      "height": 550,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3e",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1268941728,
      "version": 952,
      "versionNonce": 946075232,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771568223117,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "QnA:\n- how many DAU?\n1 billion\n\n- what features do we want to focus on? direction, navigation & ETA?\nfocus on loc updates, navigation, ETA, map rendering\n\n- how large is the road data? can we assume we have access to it?\nassume we obtained road data from different sources\n& they are raw TBs of data\n\n- should we take traffic conditions into considertaion?\nyes, very impt for accrate time estimation\n\n- how about different travel modes such as driving, walking etc.?\nneed to support different modes\n\n- should it support multi stops?\ngood to have but lets not focus on it\n\n- how about biz places & photos? how many photos are we expecting?\nhappy i brought it up, but lets not focus on those",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "QnA:\n- how many DAU?\n1 billion\n\n- what features do we want to focus on? direction, navigation & ETA?\nfocus on loc updates, navigation, ETA, map rendering\n\n- how large is the road data? can we assume we have access to it?\nassume we obtained road data from different sources\n& they are raw TBs of data\n\n- should we take traffic conditions into considertaion?\nyes, very impt for accrate time estimation\n\n- how about different travel modes such as driving, walking etc.?\nneed to support different modes\n\n- should it support multi stops?\ngood to have but lets not focus on it\n\n- how about biz places & photos? how many photos are we expecting?\nhappy i brought it up, but lets not focus on those",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "JVSQWg6ZSwZYRzcHpPRkj",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1822.8937208914685,
      "y": 179.87993969888214,
      "width": 1124.69921875,
      "height": 1875,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3f",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1776506784,
      "version": 4489,
      "versionNonce": 1908777568,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [
        {
          "id": "HVYkiwZZzbfrdVUQrnJVk",
          "type": "arrow"
        }
      ],
      "updated": 1771568241635,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "MAP 101\n\n1. positioning system: (lat, lng)\n- world is a sphere that rotates on its asix\n- top is north pole, bottom is south pole\n- lat : denotes how far north or south we are (norht is +ve 90, south is -ve 90)\n  long : denotes how far east or west we are (east is +180, west is -180)\n\n2. map projection: go from 3D to 2D\n- different ways to do map projection => most of them distort the actual geometry\n- google selected mercator projection == web mercator\n    - preserves local angles and shapes; accurate angles & shapes\n    - BUT map heaviliy distort sizes, land mass at poles appear much larger\n\n3. geo coding (addr -> (lat, lng))\n- process of converting addresses to grographic coords\n- JW 1123 street 24 == lat: 37, lng: -122)\n- conversion from (lat, lng) to addr is reverse \"geo coding\"\n- 1 way is interpolation\n    - levarages data from diff srcs such as GIS where the street network is mapped to the grographic coord space\n    - *GIS is a system that contain info such as roads, buildings, boundaries etc.\n    - *interpolation is estimating a point since u keep moving & distance only updated every few secs\n    - *this means entire city is modeled as a graph in coord space\n\n4. geo hashing ((lat, lng) -> ASCII)\n- is encoding system that encodes (lat, lng) into short string of letters & digits (ASCII characters)\n- it depicts earth as a flattened surface & recuriively divides grids into sub grids\n-> assume flattened surface is 20 000km x 10 000km\n-> after 1st division, we get 10 000km x 5000km (just divide by 2 x 2)\n-> represent them as 00, 10, 01, 11\n-> recursively divide the grids until each grid reaches a certain size threshold\n\n5. map rendering (tiling)\n- 1 fundamental concept of map rendering is tiling\n- instead of rendering the entire map as 1 large image, we break the world up into smaller tiles\n- client only downloads relevant tiles for the area the user is in, then stitches them tgt\n- there are distinct set of tiles for diff zoom lvls\n- client chooses set of tiles appropriate for the zoom lvl\n- this provides good view, without consuming too much throughput (dont want too much info at once)\n    - dont need downlaod too many tiles for high zoom\n    - instead downlaods 256x256 pixel img for the entire world\n\n6. road data processing, for nav algos (routing tiles)\n- most routing algos are variants of dijkstras or A* pth finding algos\n    - exact implementation is compelx\n- all oeprate on graph data structure\n    - nodes: intersections\n    - edges: roads\n- performance of these algos largely depend on size of graph\n    - representing entire world's network as 1 graph would consume\n    too much MEM => too large to run efficiently\n- employ subdivision technique (similar to geohashing)\n    - where we dividfe the world into smaller grids.\n    - for each grid, we convert the roads in the grid to their own small graph\n    - these grids are called routing tiles\n    - each routing tile holds reference to all the other tiles it connects to\n    - routing algo then stiches a bigger road graph as it traves these interconnected routing tiles\n- routing algos reduce MEM consumption & improve path finding performance, by only consuming\n    a small subset of the routing tiles at a time\n    & only loading additional tiles as needed\n\n* map tiles are PNG\n* routing tiles are binary files of road data\n\n7. hierarchical routing tiles (local roads, arterial roads conn districts, major highways)\n- required having data for the right lvl of detail\n    i.e. XC routing would be slow to run the routing algo against highly detailed set of street level routing tiles\n        graph stiched tgt from this would be likely too big, consume too much MEM\n\ntypically 3 sets of routing tiles:\n1. most detailed: local roads\n2. less detailed, tiles bigger: arterial roads connecting districts\n3. lowest lvl of detail: major highways connecting cities & states\n*at each lvl, there can be edges connecting to tiles at a different zoom lvl\ni.e. a freeway entracnce from local street A to freeway F (small tile to big tile)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "MAP 101\n\n1. positioning system: (lat, lng)\n- world is a sphere that rotates on its asix\n- top is north pole, bottom is south pole\n- lat : denotes how far north or south we are (norht is +ve 90, south is -ve 90)\n  long : denotes how far east or west we are (east is +180, west is -180)\n\n2. map projection: go from 3D to 2D\n- different ways to do map projection => most of them distort the actual geometry\n- google selected mercator projection == web mercator\n    - preserves local angles and shapes; accurate angles & shapes\n    - BUT map heaviliy distort sizes, land mass at poles appear much larger\n\n3. geo coding (addr -> (lat, lng))\n- process of converting addresses to grographic coords\n- JW 1123 street 24 == lat: 37, lng: -122)\n- conversion from (lat, lng) to addr is reverse \"geo coding\"\n- 1 way is interpolation\n    - levarages data from diff srcs such as GIS where the street network is mapped to the grographic coord space\n    - *GIS is a system that contain info such as roads, buildings, boundaries etc.\n    - *interpolation is estimating a point since u keep moving & distance only updated every few secs\n    - *this means entire city is modeled as a graph in coord space\n\n4. geo hashing ((lat, lng) -> ASCII)\n- is encoding system that encodes (lat, lng) into short string of letters & digits (ASCII characters)\n- it depicts earth as a flattened surface & recuriively divides grids into sub grids\n-> assume flattened surface is 20 000km x 10 000km\n-> after 1st division, we get 10 000km x 5000km (just divide by 2 x 2)\n-> represent them as 00, 10, 01, 11\n-> recursively divide the grids until each grid reaches a certain size threshold\n\n5. map rendering (tiling)\n- 1 fundamental concept of map rendering is tiling\n- instead of rendering the entire map as 1 large image, we break the world up into smaller tiles\n- client only downloads relevant tiles for the area the user is in, then stitches them tgt\n- there are distinct set of tiles for diff zoom lvls\n- client chooses set of tiles appropriate for the zoom lvl\n- this provides good view, without consuming too much throughput (dont want too much info at once)\n    - dont need downlaod too many tiles for high zoom\n    - instead downlaods 256x256 pixel img for the entire world\n\n6. road data processing, for nav algos (routing tiles)\n- most routing algos are variants of dijkstras or A* pth finding algos\n    - exact implementation is compelx\n- all oeprate on graph data structure\n    - nodes: intersections\n    - edges: roads\n- performance of these algos largely depend on size of graph\n    - representing entire world's network as 1 graph would consume\n    too much MEM => too large to run efficiently\n- employ subdivision technique (similar to geohashing)\n    - where we dividfe the world into smaller grids.\n    - for each grid, we convert the roads in the grid to their own small graph\n    - these grids are called routing tiles\n    - each routing tile holds reference to all the other tiles it connects to\n    - routing algo then stiches a bigger road graph as it traves these interconnected routing tiles\n- routing algos reduce MEM consumption & improve path finding performance, by only consuming\n    a small subset of the routing tiles at a time\n    & only loading additional tiles as needed\n\n* map tiles are PNG\n* routing tiles are binary files of road data\n\n7. hierarchical routing tiles (local roads, arterial roads conn districts, major highways)\n- required having data for the right lvl of detail\n    i.e. XC routing would be slow to run the routing algo against highly detailed set of street level routing tiles\n        graph stiched tgt from this would be likely too big, consume too much MEM\n\ntypically 3 sets of routing tiles:\n1. most detailed: local roads\n2. less detailed, tiles bigger: arterial roads connecting districts\n3. lowest lvl of detail: major highways connecting cities & states\n*at each lvl, there can be edges connecting to tiles at a different zoom lvl\ni.e. a freeway entracnce from local street A to freeway F (small tile to big tile)",
