      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "AFTER UNDERSTANDING MAPS, CONTINUE \n\nHIGH LVL DESIGN",
      "fontSize": 28,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "AFTER UNDERSTANDING MAPS, CONTINUE \n\nHIGH LVL DESIGN",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "KbbCyQ3voYs0fR-cd1MiK",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 412.21159117258446,
      "y": 1191.2208513289236,
      "width": 1094.75927734375,
      "height": 1325,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3n",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 259569568,
      "version": 2125,
      "versionNonce": 2045793888,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771574901007,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "back of Env estimations:\n1 foot = 0.3_048 meters\n1 km = 0.6_214 miles\n1km = 1000 meters\n\nStorage: 3 types of data [MEM]\n- *map of the world (refer below)\n- *road info: interviewer say TBs of road data, we transform this dataset into routing tiles\n                thus will also haveTBs of routing data\n- metadata: is trivial, skip\n\n\nMap of the world:\n- map tiling contains many set of map tiles, 1 at each zoom lvl\n- storage requiremnt\n    - estimate size of the larget tile set at the highest zoom lvl (higher the more precise)\n    lvl 0 => 1 tile (4^0)\n    lvl 1 => 4 tiles (4^2)\n    lvl 2 => 16 tiles (4^2)\n    lvl 3 => 64 tiles (4^3)\n    lvl 4 => 256 tiles (4^4)\n    ...\n    lvl 19 => ~ 280 billion tiles\n    lvl 20 => ~ 1 trillion tiles\n    lvl 21 => ~ 4.3 trillion tiles\n\n    - keep in mind that 90% of the world surface is narutral & uninhabited areas like oceans, deserts, lakes etc.\n    places like these are highly compressible as imgs\n    - can reduce storage by roughly ~80-90%\n    - storage size to a range of 44 to 88PB (use ~50PB)\n        coz 1 pixel is 1 byte, 256 * 256 = ~65_000 = 64KB per tile\n        taking away 90% means 1 trillion tiles maybe? (1000 bil)\n        100KB * 1000 bil = 100k * 1000GB = 100k * 1TB = 100 PB (upper bound)\n\n        \nServer throughput: [QPS]\n- 2 main types of requests\n    1. nav reqs -> init nav session\n    2. loc update -> user moves around during nav session\n- loc data is used downstream for number of cases\n    - shows live traffic data\n    - (to be covered in deep dive)\n\n1 bil DAU\non avg, each user uses nav for 35 mins  per week\n=> 35 billion mins per week\n=> / 7 = 5 bil mins per day\n- could send updates every sec == 5 bil mins * 60 req = 300 bil req per day = 3 million QPS\n- but client may not need to send GPS update every sec (depend on speed, stuck in traffic etc.)\n    - can batch these on client side\n    - send every 15 or 30 seconds (assume this client side optimization is made)\n    - QPS reduced to 200 000QPS\n- assume peak QPS is 5 times the avg = 200k * 5 = 1 mil",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "back of Env estimations:\n1 foot = 0.3_048 meters\n1 km = 0.6_214 miles\n1km = 1000 meters\n\nStorage: 3 types of data [MEM]\n- *map of the world (refer below)\n- *road info: interviewer say TBs of road data, we transform this dataset into routing tiles\n                thus will also haveTBs of routing data\n- metadata: is trivial, skip\n\n\nMap of the world:\n- map tiling contains many set of map tiles, 1 at each zoom lvl\n- storage requiremnt\n    - estimate size of the larget tile set at the highest zoom lvl (higher the more precise)\n    lvl 0 => 1 tile (4^0)\n    lvl 1 => 4 tiles (4^2)\n    lvl 2 => 16 tiles (4^2)\n    lvl 3 => 64 tiles (4^3)\n    lvl 4 => 256 tiles (4^4)\n    ...\n    lvl 19 => ~ 280 billion tiles\n    lvl 20 => ~ 1 trillion tiles\n    lvl 21 => ~ 4.3 trillion tiles\n\n    - keep in mind that 90% of the world surface is narutral & uninhabited areas like oceans, deserts, lakes etc.\n    places like these are highly compressible as imgs\n    - can reduce storage by roughly ~80-90%\n    - storage size to a range of 44 to 88PB (use ~50PB)\n        coz 1 pixel is 1 byte, 256 * 256 = ~65_000 = 64KB per tile\n        taking away 90% means 1 trillion tiles maybe? (1000 bil)\n        100KB * 1000 bil = 100k * 1000GB = 100k * 1TB = 100 PB (upper bound)\n\n        \nServer throughput: [QPS]\n- 2 main types of requests\n    1. nav reqs -> init nav session\n    2. loc update -> user moves around during nav session\n- loc data is used downstream for number of cases\n    - shows live traffic data\n    - (to be covered in deep dive)\n\n1 bil DAU\non avg, each user uses nav for 35 mins  per week\n=> 35 billion mins per week\n=> / 7 = 5 bil mins per day\n- could send updates every sec == 5 bil mins * 60 req = 300 bil req per day = 3 million QPS\n- but client may not need to send GPS update every sec (depend on speed, stuck in traffic etc.)\n    - can batch these on client side\n    - send every 15 or 30 seconds (assume this client side optimization is made)\n    - QPS reduced to 200 000QPS\n- assume peak QPS is 5 times the avg = 200k * 5 = 1 mil",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
