    {
      "id": "d7vEfDpnDT-UR2lMJby_P",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1245.1839511794374,
      "y": 4056.5495828886305,
      "width": 248.5198516845703,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4m",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2094588832,
      "version": 130,
      "versionNonce": 552517216,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771581890940,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep Dives 1: Data model",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep Dives 1: Data model",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "exOB3n-4wneY04pAupQ8D",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1270.9124538452645,
      "y": 4054.615745233387,
      "width": 1054.0792236328125,
      "height": 1925,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4n",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 986264480,
      "version": 2375,
      "versionNonce": 385455008,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771581904103,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "1. LOCATION SERVICE [high QPS + avail]\n- given we have 1 million location updates / sec => high QPS\nuse NoSQL DB OR column-oriented DB\n    - to support high writes\n    - loc is constantly changing & becomes stale soon as new update arrives\n        => prioritize Avail >> Consistency (no point being consistent)\n        => cassandra handles strong availability\n\n- key is (user_id, timestamp): lat/lng pair\n    - this setup, user_id is primary/ parition key & timestamp is the clutering key\n    - can partition by user_id & read latest position of specific user\n    - & then can even sort the parition by timesstamp (all same partition key stored tgt; user)\n    - retrieval of loc data for a user becomes very efficient\ndata model: key, timestamp, lat, lng, user_status, nav_mode\n\n\nUSING USER LOC data: (via streaming services)\n1. detect new / closed roads\n2. input for live traffic data\n\n* in addition to writing curr user data in our DB\n=> we wat to log this info into a message queue i.e. kafka\n=> kafka is unified, low latency, high throughput data streaming platform\n    => designed for real time data feeds\n\n-> traffic service use for live traffic updates\n-> routing tile proessing service improves routes in obj storage\n-> other services can tap in too...\n\n\n2. RENDERING SERVICE (map)\n*dive into optimizing map rendering service\n\n- rendering map service pre computes map tiles at various zoom lvls\n    => provides appropriate map details to the user\n- with each increment of zoom, # of map tiles doubles in both north-south\n& east -west dir. \n    i.e 2x2\n        4x4\n        8x8\n\n- optimization: use Vectors\n    - with WebGL, instead of sending images, u send the vector information instead (paths & polygons)\n    - client draws the paths & polygons from the vector info\n\nRASTER vs VECTOR tiles:\n1. vecotrs compresses much better than images\n2. vecotr tiles provide much bette rzomming experience\n3. with rasterized images, as client zooms from 1 lvl to another, image gets pixelated\n\n\nRASTER tiles:\n- server send images (png/ JPEG)\n- a 256 x 256 png tile contains pixels of roads, labels, colors\n\nbut client just diplays the images, so during zooming, it just appears pixelated\n\nVECTOR tiles on the other hand:\n- uses structured geometric data\n- roads = polylines\n- buildings = polygons\n- rivers = paths\n- labels = text data\n\nvectors compresses better:\n- image: stores color of every pixel, even flat areas take space\n- vecotr: stores only coords\n\nclient draws the map itself using GPU\n=> sending insn to draw the map instead of sending a picture of the map\n=> modern browsers use WebGL, GPU acceleration so it can draw well but at cheap cost vs rendering images\n\nso,\nfor raster tiles: server must query map data, render image, enconde PNG\nfor vector tiles: extract geometry, send structured data\n\n*coloring comes from style layer",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1. LOCATION SERVICE [high QPS + avail]\n- given we have 1 million location updates / sec => high QPS\nuse NoSQL DB OR column-oriented DB\n    - to support high writes\n    - loc is constantly changing & becomes stale soon as new update arrives\n        => prioritize Avail >> Consistency (no point being consistent)\n        => cassandra handles strong availability\n\n- key is (user_id, timestamp): lat/lng pair\n    - this setup, user_id is primary/ parition key & timestamp is the clutering key\n    - can partition by user_id & read latest position of specific user\n    - & then can even sort the parition by timesstamp (all same partition key stored tgt; user)\n    - retrieval of loc data for a user becomes very efficient\ndata model: key, timestamp, lat, lng, user_status, nav_mode\n\n\nUSING USER LOC data: (via streaming services)\n1. detect new / closed roads\n2. input for live traffic data\n\n* in addition to writing curr user data in our DB\n=> we wat to log this info into a message queue i.e. kafka\n=> kafka is unified, low latency, high throughput data streaming platform\n    => designed for real time data feeds\n\n-> traffic service use for live traffic updates\n-> routing tile proessing service improves routes in obj storage\n-> other services can tap in too...\n\n\n2. RENDERING SERVICE (map)\n*dive into optimizing map rendering service\n\n- rendering map service pre computes map tiles at various zoom lvls\n    => provides appropriate map details to the user\n- with each increment of zoom, # of map tiles doubles in both north-south\n& east -west dir. \n    i.e 2x2\n        4x4\n        8x8\n\n- optimization: use Vectors\n    - with WebGL, instead of sending images, u send the vector information instead (paths & polygons)\n    - client draws the paths & polygons from the vector info\n\nRASTER vs VECTOR tiles:\n1. vecotrs compresses much better than images\n2. vecotr tiles provide much bette rzomming experience\n3. with rasterized images, as client zooms from 1 lvl to another, image gets pixelated\n\n\nRASTER tiles:\n- server send images (png/ JPEG)\n- a 256 x 256 png tile contains pixels of roads, labels, colors\n\nbut client just diplays the images, so during zooming, it just appears pixelated\n\nVECTOR tiles on the other hand:\n- uses structured geometric data\n- roads = polylines\n- buildings = polygons\n- rivers = paths\n- labels = text data\n\nvectors compresses better:\n- image: stores color of every pixel, even flat areas take space\n- vecotr: stores only coords\n\nclient draws the map itself using GPU\n=> sending insn to draw the map instead of sending a picture of the map\n=> modern browsers use WebGL, GPU acceleration so it can draw well but at cheap cost vs rendering images\n\nso,\nfor raster tiles: server must query map data, render image, enconde PNG\nfor vector tiles: extract geometry, send structured data\n\n*coloring comes from style layer",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "7A0zWUi1616ueqFSTqawo",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 3733.745325241112,
      "y": 3799.7633957726525,
      "width": 803.6994018554688,
      "height": 125,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4o",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 232984480,
      "version": 878,
      "versionNonce": 1282955872,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1771584886604,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep Dives 3: navigation service\n\n1. nav service, geocoding service, shortest path service, eta service, ranker service\n2. updater services => better estimates\n3. adaptive ETA & rerouting",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep Dives 3: navigation service\n\n1. nav service, geocoding service, shortest path service, eta service, ranker service\n2. updater services => better estimates\n3. adaptive ETA & rerouting",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "CCvakPdI8DcKrCpS2HEU-",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -1244.9289306927026,
      "y": 4095.694737553703,
      "width": 1052.1993408203125,
      "height": 825,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4p",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1217295968,
      "version": 1863,
      "versionNonce": 244734560,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771577310012,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "we deal with 4 types of data:\n1. routing tiles (binary)\n2. user loc data (lat, lng, geohash)\n3. geocoding data\n4. precomputed map tiles (grids of PNGs)\n\n1. ROUTING TILES: [pre-processing + S3 storage && serialization]\n- contains terabytes of data\n- improved over time by loc data from users\n- contains large # of roads & associated metadata (i.e. names, county, lat , lng)\n- data not organized as graph data structures & not usable by most  routing algos\n\n- will need an offline processing pipeline, called \"routing tile processing service\"\n- output of this is \"routing tiles\"\n- produces 3 sets of these tiles\n- each tile contains\n    - list of graph nodes & edges\n    - representing roads & intersections\n    - also contains references to other tiles it connects to\n- tile combine tgt form an interconnected network of raods that the routing algo can consume incrementally\n\nWhere should the \"routing tile processing service\" store these tiles?\n- most graph data is kept as adj list in MEM\n- BUT there are too many tiles to keep entire sets of adj lists in MEM\n- rows in DB? => BAD!\n    - ndoes & edges as rows in DB, but its really jsut for storage purpose\n    - dont need DB features to store the routing tiles\n\nGOOD way:\n- object storage (S3) & cache it agressively on the routing service that uses those tiles\n- there are many high performance software packeages we could use to serialize the adj list to binary file\n- can organize tiles by {geohashes: _tile_, ...} fast look up for lat/ lng pair\n=> shortest path service will use these routing tiles later",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "we deal with 4 types of data:\n1. routing tiles (binary)\n2. user loc data (lat, lng, geohash)\n3. geocoding data\n4. precomputed map tiles (grids of PNGs)\n\n1. ROUTING TILES: [pre-processing + S3 storage && serialization]\n- contains terabytes of data\n- improved over time by loc data from users\n- contains large # of roads & associated metadata (i.e. names, county, lat , lng)\n- data not organized as graph data structures & not usable by most  routing algos\n\n- will need an offline processing pipeline, called \"routing tile processing service\"\n- output of this is \"routing tiles\"\n- produces 3 sets of these tiles\n- each tile contains\n    - list of graph nodes & edges\n    - representing roads & intersections\n    - also contains references to other tiles it connects to\n- tile combine tgt form an interconnected network of raods that the routing algo can consume incrementally\n\nWhere should the \"routing tile processing service\" store these tiles?\n- most graph data is kept as adj list in MEM\n- BUT there are too many tiles to keep entire sets of adj lists in MEM\n- rows in DB? => BAD!\n    - ndoes & edges as rows in DB, but its really jsut for storage purpose\n    - dont need DB features to store the routing tiles\n\nGOOD way:\n- object storage (S3) & cache it agressively on the routing service that uses those tiles\n- there are many high performance software packeages we could use to serialize the adj list to binary file\n- can organize tiles by {geohashes: _tile_, ...} fast look up for lat/ lng pair\n=> shortest path service will use these routing tiles later",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "929BVkjpRQHXkE8z8-bCw",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -98.05088463152833,
      "y": 4015.446092974613,
      "width": 1311.7591552734375,
      "height": 700,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b4q",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1042826144,
      "version": 1170,
      "versionNonce": 289062816,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771579022958,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. USER LOC DATA \n- is valuable\n- updates road data & routing tiles + map data (via stream processing services)\n- build DB of live & historical traffic data\n\n*require DB with write heavy workload well + horizontally scale\n=> cassandra (NoSQL)\n\nsingle row:\n- user_id:        101\n- timestamp:     1635740977\n- user_status:    active\n- nav_mode: driving\n- location:       (lat, lng)\n\n3. GEO CODING DB\n\nstores places & corresponding lat/ lng pair\n- use KV DB such as Redis for fast reads => frequent reads, with infrequent writes\n- use it to convert origin/ dest. to lat/ lng pairs\n- then pass it to route planner service\n\n4. PRECOMPUTED IMAGES (WORLD MAP)\n- user asks for map of area, we need nearby roads & compute an image that represents that area with all the roads & related details\n    - these computations would be heavy & redundant\n    - will be helpful to compute them all first\n    - precompute images at different zoom lvls & store them at the CDN, backed by object storage (S3)\n    ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. USER LOC DATA \n- is valuable\n- updates road data & routing tiles + map data (via stream processing services)\n- build DB of live & historical traffic data\n\n*require DB with write heavy workload well + horizontally scale\n=> cassandra (NoSQL)\n\nsingle row:\n- user_id:        101\n- timestamp:     1635740977\n- user_status:    active\n- nav_mode: driving\n- location:       (lat, lng)\n\n3. GEO CODING DB\n\nstores places & corresponding lat/ lng pair\n- use KV DB such as Redis for fast reads => frequent reads, with infrequent writes\n- use it to convert origin/ dest. to lat/ lng pairs\n- then pass it to route planner service\n\n4. PRECOMPUTED IMAGES (WORLD MAP)\n- user asks for map of area, we need nearby roads & compute an image that represents that area with all the roads & related details\n    - these computations would be heavy & redundant\n    - will be helpful to compute them all first\n    - precompute images at different zoom lvls & store them at the CDN, backed by object storage (S3)\n    ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
