    {
      "id": "Yjygg_zFR2aDQM3VOOsOH",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1277.695069969351,
      "y": 4003.987159969133,
      "width": 599.8995361328125,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b5J",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 830627424,
      "version": 3,
      "versionNonce": 1051709344,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771581901744,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Deep Dives 2: loc(streaming) & rendering service(vector tiles)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Deep Dives 2: loc(streaming) & rendering service(vector tiles)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "GPG0AGqXbAKp4tsOaZhW3",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 3763.447434386351,
      "y": 3948.341262924854,
      "width": 1283.67919921875,
      "height": 2750,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b5K",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1561431648,
      "version": 4157,
      "versionNonce": 1373222496,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1771586552983,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "*Finding fastest route\n\n1. Geocoding service\n- resolve address to loc in (lat, lng)\n- nav service calls this to geo code the origin & destination\n    then passes (lat, lng) downstream to find routes\n\n2. Route planner service\n- computes a suggested route that is optimized for travel time according to\n    1. current traffic\n    2. road conditions\n(interacts with the service that will be discussed)\n\n3. shortest path service\n- recives start & end -> returns top-k shortest path without considering\n    traffic or current conditions\n- caching the routes could be good because the graph rarely changes\n\n- shortest path serice runs a variation of A* path finding algo against routing tiles in obj store\n    1.\n    - algo receive the start & end in lat/ lng pairs\n    - they are then converted to geohashes which are used to load the start & endpoints of routing tiles\n    2.\n    - algo starts from the origin routing tile, traveses the graph data structure\n    - then hydrates additional neighbouring tiles from the object store (or local cache if its laoded b4)\n        as it expands the serach area\n    - this is how algo can \"enter\" the bigger tiles containing only highways\n    (u always have the start & end to get to the other side of the tile)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n4. ETA service\n- with list of shortest paths, the ETA service is called for each possible route & gets a time estimate\n- ETA service uses machine learnign to predic the ETAs based on the current traffic & historical data\n    (from the traffic DB via the update traffic service)\n\n- 1 challenge here is we not only look at current time, but also consider how the traffic will look like 10-20 mins later\n- these kinds of challenges need to be addressed at an algorithmic lvl & will not be discussed in this section\n\n5. RANKER service\n- once route planner obtains the ETA predictions, passes info to the ranker\n- applies possible filters as defined by the user (include toll roads, or avoid freeways etc.)\n- ranks routes & returns fastest to slowest to navigation service\n\n\n\na. UPDATER services (ROUTING TILE PROCESSING & TRAFFIC UPDATER)\n- service taps into kafka loc update stream& asynchronously update some of the important DBs to keep them up to date\n    - traffic DB, routing tiles are e.g.s\n1. ROUTING TILE PROCESSING service is responsible for transforming road dataset with newly found roads & road closures into\n    continuously updated set of routing tiles\n2. TRAFFIC UPDATE service extracts traffic condtions from the streams of location updates sent by the active users\n    - insight needs to be fed to live traffic DB\n    - enables ETA service to provide more accurate estimates\n\n\nb. IMPROVEMENT: adaptive ETA & rerouting\n- currently dont support changing ETA as time passes\n- & no re-routing for better routes\n\nDETECT users\n- need to track all active navigaters & update them on ETA continuously\n1. how to track actively navigating users?\n2. how to store the data, so we can efficiently locate the affected users\n\nnaively,\nwe can store users with their routes like such:\nuser_1: s_1, s_2, s_3 ... s_k\nuser_2: s_4, s_5, s_3 ... s_n\nuser_3: s_10, s_11, s_3 ... s_n\nuser_4: s_4, s_5, s_6 ... s_n\nif there is an incident in s_3, user 1 2 & 3 are affected\nbut time to find is O(n*m)\n\nhow to better this?\nfor each actively navigating user\nwe keep current routing tile, routing tile at next resolution, & the intermediate tile ------->\n\nto find if user is affected by traffic change, we just check last val of every active user row\nelse the user is not imapcted O(n) time => quickly filter out users\n\nhow do users know re-route is possible? always keep track of all possible routes for a\nnavigating user, recalculate the ETAs regularly & notify the user if a new route\nwith a shorter ETA is found\n\nDELIVERY PROTOCOLS\n- server needs reliabl eway of pushing all these push notifications to clients\n- options include mobile push notifs, long polling, websocket, & SSE\n\n* for push notifs, consider (mobile push notifs, long polling, WS, SSE)\n    - mobile push notifs not great\n        - payload size is limited (4096 bytes for IOS) => 100KBs of img data\n        - doesnt support web apps\n    - WS is considered better than long polling coz lighter no extra oveerhead\n        - over head in HTTP req-res being sent for every single msg\n        - vs HTTP header done once in WS, then the rest of the time its just payload\n    - so ~~mobile push notifs~~ & ~~long polling~~\n    - then WS vs SSE?\n        - both works but lean towards WS\n        - WS supports bidirectional comms & features such as last mile delivery might require bi directional real time comms\n            (basically client acks the new route and server now knows; it then can update active user's new route)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "*Finding fastest route\n\n1. Geocoding service\n- resolve address to loc in (lat, lng)\n- nav service calls this to geo code the origin & destination\n    then passes (lat, lng) downstream to find routes\n\n2. Route planner service\n- computes a suggested route that is optimized for travel time according to\n    1. current traffic\n    2. road conditions\n(interacts with the service that will be discussed)\n\n3. shortest path service\n- recives start & end -> returns top-k shortest path without considering\n    traffic or current conditions\n- caching the routes could be good because the graph rarely changes\n\n- shortest path serice runs a variation of A* path finding algo against routing tiles in obj store\n    1.\n    - algo receive the start & end in lat/ lng pairs\n    - they are then converted to geohashes which are used to load the start & endpoints of routing tiles\n    2.\n    - algo starts from the origin routing tile, traveses the graph data structure\n    - then hydrates additional neighbouring tiles from the object store (or local cache if its laoded b4)\n        as it expands the serach area\n    - this is how algo can \"enter\" the bigger tiles containing only highways\n    (u always have the start & end to get to the other side of the tile)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n4. ETA service\n- with list of shortest paths, the ETA service is called for each possible route & gets a time estimate\n- ETA service uses machine learnign to predic the ETAs based on the current traffic & historical data\n    (from the traffic DB via the update traffic service)\n\n- 1 challenge here is we not only look at current time, but also consider how the traffic will look like 10-20 mins later\n- these kinds of challenges need to be addressed at an algorithmic lvl & will not be discussed in this section\n\n5. RANKER service\n- once route planner obtains the ETA predictions, passes info to the ranker\n- applies possible filters as defined by the user (include toll roads, or avoid freeways etc.)\n- ranks routes & returns fastest to slowest to navigation service\n\n\n\na. UPDATER services (ROUTING TILE PROCESSING & TRAFFIC UPDATER)\n- service taps into kafka loc update stream& asynchronously update some of the important DBs to keep them up to date\n    - traffic DB, routing tiles are e.g.s\n1. ROUTING TILE PROCESSING service is responsible for transforming road dataset with newly found roads & road closures into\n    continuously updated set of routing tiles\n2. TRAFFIC UPDATE service extracts traffic condtions from the streams of location updates sent by the active users\n    - insight needs to be fed to live traffic DB\n    - enables ETA service to provide more accurate estimates\n\n\nb. IMPROVEMENT: adaptive ETA & rerouting\n- currently dont support changing ETA as time passes\n- & no re-routing for better routes\n\nDETECT users\n- need to track all active navigaters & update them on ETA continuously\n1. how to track actively navigating users?\n2. how to store the data, so we can efficiently locate the affected users\n\nnaively,\nwe can store users with their routes like such:\nuser_1: s_1, s_2, s_3 ... s_k\nuser_2: s_4, s_5, s_3 ... s_n\nuser_3: s_10, s_11, s_3 ... s_n\nuser_4: s_4, s_5, s_6 ... s_n\nif there is an incident in s_3, user 1 2 & 3 are affected\nbut time to find is O(n*m)\n\nhow to better this?\nfor each actively navigating user\nwe keep current routing tile, routing tile at next resolution, & the intermediate tile ------->\n\nto find if user is affected by traffic change, we just check last val of every active user row\nelse the user is not imapcted O(n) time => quickly filter out users\n\nhow do users know re-route is possible? always keep track of all possible routes for a\nnavigating user, recalculate the ETAs regularly & notify the user if a new route\nwith a shorter ETA is found\n\nDELIVERY PROTOCOLS\n- server needs reliabl eway of pushing all these push notifications to clients\n- options include mobile push notifs, long polling, websocket, & SSE\n\n* for push notifs, consider (mobile push notifs, long polling, WS, SSE)\n    - mobile push notifs not great\n        - payload size is limited (4096 bytes for IOS) => 100KBs of img data\n        - doesnt support web apps\n    - WS is considered better than long polling coz lighter no extra oveerhead\n        - over head in HTTP req-res being sent for every single msg\n        - vs HTTP header done once in WS, then the rest of the time its just payload\n    - so ~~mobile push notifs~~ & ~~long polling~~\n    - then WS vs SSE?\n        - both works but lean towards WS\n        - WS supports bidirectional comms & features such as last mile delivery might require bi directional real time comms\n            (basically client acks the new route and server now knows; it then can update active user's new route)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
